This is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped` gives you a fresh `DbContext` per request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app has a single scope for its entire lifetime, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is reused everywhere, causing stale/persisted data.

### Fixes

**Option 1: Use `AddTransient`**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
This gives a new instance every time one is injected. Simple, but you lose control over disposal.

**Option 2: Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create manual scopes** (recommended)
```csharp
// Registration (keep AddScoped)
builder.Services.AddScoped<MyDbContext>();

// In your page/viewmodel, inject the factory:
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

    public async Task LoadDataAsync()
    {
        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
        // db is fresh and disposed when scope exits
    }
}
```

**Option 2 is preferred** because you get deterministic disposal and a clean change-tracker on each operation — just like a per-request scope in ASP.NET Core.
